org.mindswap.owl
Interface OWLModel

All Known Subinterfaces:
OWLKnowledgeBase, OWLOntology
All Known Implementing Classes:
OWLKnowledgeBaseImpl, OWLModelImpl, OWLOntologyImpl
public interface OWLModel

A OWLModel is the data structure to manage a set of OWL axioms and assertions. It is structured hierarchically, that is, it consists of a base model and may contain any number of sub models, whereby sub models may again contain sub models. If this model is actually a OWLKnowledgeBase then its sub models are ontologies that were loaded into the KB. On the other hand, if it is a OWLOntology then the base model represents the document that was loaded from a (remote) file, a stream, or a reader, and its sub models are imported ontologies (if any) of this base ontology.

getBaseModel

OWLModel getBaseModel()
Get the model where the changes will be made (create and add) by default. (Note that set and remove methods invoked on this model my cause updates throughout the entire model, i.e., also in sub models of this model.)

If this model is a KB then it is the base ontology of the KB. At the creation time of each KB an empty ontology is created to be the base ontology of the KB. All createXXX and addXXX methods will actually modify this base ontology. However, removeXXX and setXXX methods may modify any sub ontology in the KB, provided that it is not in read-only mode.

If this model is a ontology then the base model is the ontology not containing the statements of its imported ontologies (if any).

Returns:
The base model.

refresh

void refresh()
If a reasoner is attached this method will force it to rebind this model, thus, refreshing all its content.

This method is

startBulkUpdate

void startBulkUpdate()
Use this method when a bulk of modifying operations should be done. This will temporarily deactivate refreshing that would otherwise be done after each single operation is finished, thus, preventing additional delays consumed by refreshing.

Use endBulkUpdate(boolean) to indicate that the bulk operation is complete.

This model will not perform refresh(), classify(), nor prepare() operations while a bulk update is not yet finished.

This method is reentrant. Repeated invocation without interleaving invocations of endBulkUpdate(boolean) is possible to support nested bulk updates. Note that endBulkUpdate(boolean) needs to be invoked exactly as often as this method was invoked in order to entirely end a bulk update.

Use this method to announce the end of a modifying bulk operation.

Parameters:
refresh - If true and this method invocation represents the completion of the outermost bulk operation (i.e. isBulkUpdate() returns false afterwards) this method will also perform a refresh().

isConsistent

boolean isConsistent()
Check if the model is consistent or not. Since this is a standard inferencing task a reasoner needs to be attached, otherwise the result is meaningless.

Returns:
true if (i) this model is consistent according to the attached reasoner, (ii) there is no reasoner attached, or (ii) the reasoner used does not support consistency check. false otherwise.

classify

void classify()
Tell the reasoner (if any) to compute the subclass relations between all the named classes and find the instances of each class. The results will be cached and subsequent calls to query the model will use the cache. This call has no effect if reasoner does not support classification.

createIndividual

OWLIndividual createIndividual(java.net.URI rdfType,
                               java.net.URI uri)
Either create a plain individual, i.e., a resource that does not has the property rdf:type set, or an individual where rdf:type refers to the given resource.

Note that this method does not check if the resource identified by rdfType is known to be a OWL class. Consequently, this model may transit to OWL Full if this model does not entail the resource referred to by rdfType to be a OWL class.

Parameters:
rdfType - The URI to be set for rdf:type. If null no rdf:type statement will be added to the returned resource.
uri - The URI for the individual, or null for an anonymous individual.
Returns:
A new individual identified by the given URI, if not null.

getDataType

OWLDataType getDataType(java.lang.Class<?> clazz)
This method can be used to retrieve the OWL datatype to which a given Java class can be mapped. This is not a fully fledged (generic) type mapping mechanism as it supports only for primitive Java types (int.class, ...), their wrapper types (Integer.class, ...) and a few common types, namely URI, URL, Date, and Calendar.

Parameters:
clazz - The Java class.
Returns:
The OWL datatype to which the Java type is mapped, or null if the type can not be directly mapped.

remove

void remove(OWLIndividual ind,
            boolean recursive)
Removes all statements from the model where the given OWL individual is the object or subject, therefore removing each occurrence of the given individual.

If the recursive parameter is set, the method iterates recursively through all properties of the given individual and removes them all.

Parameters:
ind - The individual to remove.
recursive - true, if recursive removal is desired. false otherwise.

getIncomingProperty

OWLIndividual getIncomingProperty(OWLObjectProperty prop,
                                  OWLIndividual ind)
Get the individual that refers to the given OWL individual via the given object property. Using RDF terminology, we can say that this method returns the subject s that refers via the predicate p (prop) to the object o (ind).

If the underlying model contains multiple individuals that relate via the property to the same individual, the first one found is returned, i.e., it should only be used for inverse functional properties (provided that the underlying model is consistent). In case of standard and functional properties it is recommended to use getIncomingProperties(OWLObjectProperty, OWLIndividual) instead.

Parameters:
prop - The connecting property.
ind - The object individual.
Returns:
The subject individual, or null if no such relation exists in this model.

isLockSupported

boolean isLockSupported()
Checks if this implementation supports locking to synchronize concurrent access.

Returns:
true if this model can be locked for read and/or write access.
See Also:
lockForRead(), lockForWrite(), releaseLock()

lockForRead

void lockForRead()
Lock the model for read operations. Multiple read operations are allowed for the same model. When the model is locked for reading no operation that would modify the model should be called.

This method is reentrant so an application can have nested critical sections. However, the application must call releaseLock() as often as this method was invoked to release the lock.

Throws:
java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - If the implementation does not support locking, i.e., isLockSupported() returns false.
See Also:
isLockSupported(), lockForWrite(), releaseLock()

lockForWrite

void lockForWrite()
Lock the model for write operations. No other thread can access the model while there is a write lock.

This method is reentrant so an application can have nested critical sections. However, the application must call releaseLock() as often as this method was invoked to release the lock.

Throws:
java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - If the implementation does not support locking, i.e., isLockSupported() returns false.
See Also:
isLockSupported(), lockForRead(), releaseLock()

releaseLock

void releaseLock()
Releases the lock form the matching lockForXXX method. If there was no lock set before this method has no effect.

Since locking is reentrant an application must call this method as often as the matching lockForXXX method was invoked.

Throws:
java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - If the implementation does not support locking, i.e., isLockSupported() returns false.
See Also:
isLockSupported(), lockForRead(), lockForWrite()

parseLiteral

OWLIndividual parseLiteral(java.lang.String literal)
Parse the given RDF/XML string and add all triples to this model. In addition, this method searches for a unique root node (RDF resource) in the RDF graph represented by the string and tries to view and return the root node as an OWLIndividual. Consequently, the RDF graph should form a tree (i.e. should not be a forest with multiple root nodes) and should not have cycles involving the root node, i.e., there should be (i) exactly one resource (individual) that (ii) occurs exactly once as the subject and never as the object in any triple of the graph (never transitively involved in a cycle). If there are multiple root nodes then any one is selected and returned.

This method is intended to be used for parsing embedded XML literals which are RDF/XML fragments and contain an individual that might be (recursively) associated to other individuals or data values using properties.

Parameters:
literal - The RDF/XML literal.
Returns:
The individual or null in case parsing failed for whatever reason.
